@G[c3 stills_93.png]@L  

		@H Historical Background @L
		In the year 245 BC, the Romans have conquered the city that will be henceforth known as Brundisium. The site was first settled in 16th century BC during the Bronze Age, archeologists have discovered shards of Mycenaean pottery in the area, and it is therefore likely that first settlers were ancient Mycenaean Greeks since ancient historian Herodotus spoke of the locals as of Mycenean origin. @L@L
		At the time of Rome's rise to power, however, the locals were of Messapian culture, which is an Italic group of peoples. Its Messapian name of "Brention" which means "deer's head" likely referred to shape of the cities harbor. @L@L The city of Brundisium had vital importance as a trade hub and strategic port in southern Italia. In future conflicts and especially after the Punic Wars, it played a vital part as a crucial supply hub and naval base for the Romans. @L@L
		Brundisium received its Roman citizenship rights in the Social War and was made a free port by Sulla. @L@L
		Note that at the start of this assignment, Rome is no longer a kingdom but rather a republic, therefore you should treat requests from the "Emperor" as if they were from the Roman Senate. @L@L

		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]
		@H Instructions @L
		Welcome to Brundisium governor. Roman armies sufficiently pacified the locals, so your only concern is still going to be city development. I wish for Brundisium to develop into a regional trade center. Use the ample local resources and fertile land in order to create a city of Roman standards, with adequate housing for all the workers as well as a sizable harbor area to facilitate overseas trade. @L@L
		In Brundisium, you will familiarize yourself with a new step in each city's development. Before craftsmen who can create processed goods are attracted to your city, you will have to rely on agricultural activity, mining, or lumber industry to sustain the early growth of your colony. Fortunately, this process is helped by the monthly state subsidy of 100 denarii, granted to all fledgling colonies. @L@L
		If you find the time in your busy schedule, I advise you to familiarize yourself with large scale constructions as well, as this vital skillset will be useful in the future assignments. Good luck governor, and do not disappoint the people of Rome. @L@L@L

		@H Edicts @L
		@Abundant @Clay @Soil - Once the city has 5 active clay pits, you receive +2 clay and +2 sand into any warehouse that accepts these monthly. @L@L
		@Cultural @Influence - Trading with any cities in Greece will cause an extra drop of -2 favor per year. Libraries are enabled at the start from this map onwards. (Cities in Greece are Corcyra and Epidamnos)@L

		@H Additional Information @L 
		The terrain on most maps will retain its fundamental structure of the base campaign map, but with rocks/cliffs/water added to break up standard blocks and offer more of a challenge. Almost all maps should start with a pre-built city from historical standpoint, but since most people would not like to deal with pre-built areas, for the sake of gameplay, pre-built structures on the map will be limited. @L@L
		You will also be introduced to a new concept also present on all future maps: the subsidy mechanic. This will be explained in detail in a separate message during this mission. @L@L@L
		The military and peaceful paths have been merged into one, and you should play all the maps in order for the recommended experience. Economic missions will generally be more difficult, featuring logistical and space constraints, but military missions will have economic and developmental constraints as well. @L@L
		If you wish to learn how to construct monuments, achieve 1500 population and a side objective with marble will be unlocked. @L@L
		@H Persistent Events @L
		Grand Temple to Mercury unlocks plaza. Subsidies, lasting until 10 prosperity rating, give 100 dn. per month. Workshops only unlock after the subsidy expires. Due to game limitations, starting prices for goods will be adjusted after 1 in-game month has passed. @L@L@L@L

