@G26 
		@H Message @L
		This is a tutorial message for people who might not be familiar with monuments and their bonuses. To build monuments, you place a foundation and pay the upfront cost; then connect a middle tile of the construction site to the road network. Add an architects' guild and a work camp on the same road layout. Make sure to have access to warehouses stocked with timber, bricks, stone, marble, or gold (gold is only required for the Pantheon).
		@G[camp_and_architect.png]
		@L@L Work camps will collect resources from warehouses and deliver them to the sites that require them, then an architect from the guild will inspect the site, which can take multiple trips. Additional work camps closer to resources and architects' guilds closer to the building site will help to speed up construction. Note that some monuments have multiple stages to complete which are visually represented. Additionally, most monuments, all forts and temples, as well as highway tiles have a monthly levy (aka upkeep cost) associated with them. Consider building a highway when your city is unable to meet all the required quotas for speedier caravans as well as immigration. @L@L
		@G[light_and_carava.png]
		The caravanserai and lighthouse are monuments specifically related to trade. Both offer the city the choice of a trading policy which boosts trader capacity or prices for imports/exports. The caravanserai consumes 20 units of food (100 units is 1 granary/warehouse cartload) for any caravans that spawn into the map but reduces land interruption event length by 50 percent. Note that it will require a granary with market lady access enabled to collect the food or its benefits and policy will cease to function. Also note that caravans do not need to physically travel to the caravanserai so it will not impact your caravans' destinations on the map. @L@L
		The lighthouse needs to be built near water and it burns 4.8 cartloads of timber per year to function (half the output of a single timber yard) and its benefit is that fishing boats travel 10 percent faster and sea trade disruptions are cleared 50 percent faster. If there is not enough timber to burn the lighthouse will cease to function. The lighthouse collects timber from a warehouse, and the warehouse needs to allow lighthouse access. @L@L
		@G[city_mint_full.png]@L
		The city mint requires a Senate to be built and will offer two options to the governor: either convert cartloads of gold into money for the city and if city contains a governor's residence, it also provides extra personal funds; or it can also be used to melt city money into cartloads of gold that can be used for building the Pantheon on maps without local or tradable gold, or exports if prices allow this to be viable.   @L@L
		@G42 @L Why would a governor invest into monuments? I will list some examples of uses for monuments but there are many, and Augustus has converted some original structures into monuments as well so it's always up to the governor to decide. @L@L
		@G[mausoleums.png]
		- Mausoleums (first 5 large ones or 10 small ones) give the city a small global health bonus. Augustus features a global health malus mechanic, which impacts the city health as it grows in population. Mausoleums will help to mitigate this debuff. They are also undesirable in their immediate area but give bonuses to houses further away from them. Mausoleums also provide worship space for all gods, same as an oracle.  @L@L
		@G[hippo_coli.png]
		- Colosseum and hippodrome will give all houses, even without direct access to them, a +5 bonus to entertainment, regardless of where they are constructed. If you build both, houses get +10 so it stacks. For context, an increase of 10 entertainment points is a requirement to evolve from large to luxury palace or all the entertainment needed for large casa.  @L@L
		- Grand temples have global bonuses for building them and provide 4000 worship space for their specific god. The Pantheon provides worship for all gods at once but less space. Note that to get access to any main bonus you only need to construct said temple. To get the benefits of epithets to your housing, they will need to have access to that god's priests. Any priests will do, even small temples will provide the required coverage in your blocks. @L@L
		I will list the bonuses for building the grand temples and then also list their epithets. These are additional bonuses you can choose from after a grand temple is completed and fully staffed. Each grand temple can only have 1 epithet, and it cannot be changed unless you delete the monument so choose what would benefit your city the most wisely. Each grand temple has substantial upkeep and worker cost. You can increase the maximum number of grand temples you can have in the game's difficulty settings. @L@L
		@G[gt_ceres.png] 
		- Ceres grand temple: gives cart pushers from farms 50 percent speed bonus.@L Fecunda epithet - houses covered by a Ceres priest consume 20 percent less food.@L Frigifera epithet - Ceres temples act as markets and collect and distribute one locally produced food type as well as oil. @L@L
		@G[gt_neptune.png]
		- Neptune grand temple: boosts reservoir and fountain range by +1 tile, reduces water services labor costs by 50 percent, boosts trading ships travel time by 25 percent, as well as reduces sickness growth in all houses in the city.@L Equester epithet - sends chariots from the Neptune grand temple as destination walkers to hippodrome if one is present in the city.@L Adiutor epithet - gives houses covered by Neptune priests extra 5 percent population space and make the grand temple itself act as a reservoir coverage for nearby fountains, therefore allowing water access to areas previously inaccessible with water.  @L@L
		@G[gt_mercury.png]
		- Mercury grand temple: land and sea traders get 50 percent extra goods capacity, and land and native traders get extra 20% speed bonus.@L Fortunus epithet - reduces pottery and furniture consumption in houses covered by priests of Mercury by 20 percent.@L Mercurius Mercator epithet - reduces oil and wine consumption in houses covered by priests of Mercury by 20 percent.@L In the Reconquered Campaign, GT to Mercury also unlocks the plaza on every map. If you struggle with desirability, try to build blocks on high ground to get a free boost to all houses built on high ground; a similar bonus applies to houses adjacent to water.  @L@L
		@G[gt_mars.png]
		- Mars grand temple: allows your city to construct 4 extra forts, up to maximum of 10 total and acts as a second barracks.@L Ultor epithet - makes all priests of Mars generate food as they walk past houses which they will then later deliver to the supply post for the soldiers to eat, this food is generated so it does not increase consumption.@L Quirinus epithet - reduces all goods consumption in houses covered by all Mars priests by 10 percent.  @L@L
		@G[gt_venus.png]
		- Venus grand temple: decor has boosted desirability, houses can stockpile more goods in them and devolve slower.@L Verticordia epithet - acts as a second wine type produced within the city, Venus temples can also be set to distribute wine that they gather based on city pop.@L Genetrix epithet - Venus priests give +10 entertainment to housing and greatly boost desirability of houses they cover.  @L@L
		@G[phanteon.png]
		- Pantheon grand temple: reduces levy costs for religious buildings in the city by 25 percent, allows to hold annual festivals to chosen deity and when gods are happy, prevents events such as contaminated water, collapses of mines and clay pits from occurring in the city.@L Ara Maxima epithet - all small and large temples will send an extra priest as a destination walker to the pantheon.@L Roma Aetherna epithet - gives houses covered by the pantheon walker ability to evolve one extra step even without having the prerequisite needs met (helpful on maps without academies and high prosperity).  @L@L
		As always consider reading the manual or watching my videos on feature breakdowns on YouTube for more information. @L@L@L@L

